{"award_age":85.0,"bio_image":"full\/c6a84e1248e01b599f188d90e6da7a8715d2f37a.jpg","category":"Physics","country":"United States","date_of_birth":"1924-08-19T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"2011-05-07T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/b\/b4\/Nobel_Prize_2009-Press_Conference_KVA-23.jpg\/200px-Nobel_Prize_2009-Press_Conference_KVA-23.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Willard_S._Boyle","mini_bio":"<p><b>Willard Sterling Boyle<\/b>, <span style=\"font-size:85%;\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Order_of_Canada\" title=\"Order of Canada\">CC<\/a><\/span> (August 19, 1924\u00a0\u2013 May 7, 2011) was a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Canadian\" title=\"Canadian\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Canadian<\/a>-<a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Americans\" title=\"Americans\">American<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Physicist\" title=\"Physicist\">physicist<\/a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-NYT_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Willard_S._Boyle#cite_note-NYT-4\"><span>[<\/span>4<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> pioneer in the field of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Laser\" title=\"Laser\">laser<\/a> technology and co-inventor of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Charge-coupled_device\" title=\"Charge-coupled device\">charge-coupled device<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-CBC_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Willard_S._Boyle#cite_note-CBC-5\"><span>[<\/span>5<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> On October 6, 2009, it was announced that he would share the 2009 <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physics\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physics\">Nobel Prize in Physics<\/a> for \"the invention of an imaging semiconductor circuit\u2014the CCD sensor, which has become an electronic eye in almost all areas of photography\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-Noble_Prize_bio_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Willard_S._Boyle#cite_note-Noble_Prize_bio-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>Born in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Amherst,_Nova_Scotia\" title=\"Amherst, Nova Scotia\">Amherst, Nova Scotia<\/a>, on August 19, 1924, Boyle was the son of a medical doctor and moved to Quebec with his father and mother Beatrice when he was three.<sup id=\"cite_ref-big_idea_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Willard_S._Boyle#cite_note-big_idea-6\"><span>[<\/span>6<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> He was home schooled by his mother until age fourteen, when he attended <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Montreal\" title=\"Montreal\">Montreal<\/a>'s <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Lower_Canada_College\" title=\"Lower Canada College\">Lower Canada College<\/a> to complete his secondary education.<sup id=\"cite_ref-big_idea_6-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Willard_S._Boyle#cite_note-big_idea-6\"><span>[<\/span>6<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> Boyle attended <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/McGill_University\" title=\"McGill University\">McGill University<\/a>, but his education was interrupted in 1943, when he joined the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Royal_Canadian_Navy\" title=\"Royal Canadian Navy\">Royal Canadian Navy<\/a> during <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/World_War_II\" title=\"World War II\">World War II<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-big_idea_6-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Willard_S._Boyle#cite_note-big_idea-6\"><span>[<\/span>6<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> He was loaned to the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/British_Royal_Navy\" title=\"British Royal Navy\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Britain's Royal Navy<\/a>, where he was learning how to land <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Supermarine_Spitfire\" title=\"Supermarine Spitfire\">Spitfires<\/a> on <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Aircraft_carrier\" title=\"Aircraft carrier\">aircraft carriers<\/a> as the war ended.<sup id=\"cite_ref-big_idea_6-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Willard_S._Boyle#cite_note-big_idea-6\"><span>[<\/span>6<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> He gained a BSc (1947), MSc (1948) and PhD (1950) from McGill University.<sup id=\"cite_ref-McGill_7-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Willard_S._Boyle#cite_note-McGill-7\"><span>[<\/span>7<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>After receiving his doctorate, Boyle spent one year at Canada's Radiation Lab and two years teaching physics at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Royal_Military_College_of_Canada\" title=\"Royal Military College of Canada\">Royal Military College of Canada<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-big_idea_6-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Willard_S._Boyle#cite_note-big_idea-6\"><span>[<\/span>6<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> In 1953 Boyle joined <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Bell_Labs\" title=\"Bell Labs\">Bell Labs<\/a> where he invented the first continuously operating <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ruby_laser\" title=\"Ruby laser\">ruby laser<\/a> with Don Nelson in 1962,<sup id=\"cite_ref-canpress_8-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Willard_S._Boyle#cite_note-canpress-8\"><span>[<\/span>8<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> and was named on the first patent for a semiconductor injection laser.<sup id=\"cite_ref-canpress_8-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Willard_S._Boyle#cite_note-canpress-8\"><span>[<\/span>8<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> He was made director of Space Science and Exploratory Studies at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Bell_Labs\" title=\"Bell Labs\">Bell Labs<\/a> subsidiary Bellcomm in 1962, providing support for the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Apollo_space_program\" title=\"Apollo space program\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Apollo space program<\/a> and helping to select lunar landing sites.<sup id=\"cite_ref-canpress_8-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Willard_S._Boyle#cite_note-canpress-8\"><span>[<\/span>8<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> He returned to Bell Labs in 1964, working on the development of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Integrated_circuits\" title=\"Integrated circuits\" class=\"mw-redirect\">integrated circuits<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-canpress_8-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Willard_S._Boyle#cite_note-canpress-8\"><span>[<\/span>8<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>In 1969, Boyle and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/George_E._Smith\" title=\"George E. Smith\">George E. Smith<\/a> invented the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Charge-coupled_device\" title=\"Charge-coupled device\">charge-coupled device<\/a> (CCD), for which they have jointly received the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Franklin_Institute\" title=\"Franklin Institute\">Franklin Institute<\/a>'s <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Stuart_Ballantine_Medal\" title=\"Stuart Ballantine Medal\">Stuart Ballantine Medal<\/a> in 1973, the 1974 <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/IEEE_Morris_N._Liebmann_Memorial_Award\" title=\"IEEE Morris N. Liebmann Memorial Award\">IEEE Morris N. Liebmann Memorial Award<\/a>, the 2006 <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Charles_Stark_Draper_Prize\" title=\"Charles Stark Draper Prize\">Charles Stark Draper Prize<\/a>, and the 2009 <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physics\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physics\">Nobel Prize in Physics<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-McGill_7-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Willard_S._Boyle#cite_note-McGill-7\"><span>[<\/span>7<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-canpress_8-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Willard_S._Boyle#cite_note-canpress-8\"><span>[<\/span>8<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> However, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Eugene_I._Gordon\" title=\"Eugene I. Gordon\">Eugene Gordon<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Michael_Francis_Tompsett\" title=\"Michael Francis Tompsett\">Mike Tompsett<\/a>, two now-retired colleagues from Bell labs, claim that its application to photography was not invented by Boyle.<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Willard_S._Boyle#cite_note-9\"><span>[<\/span>9<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> The CCD allowed <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/NASA\" title=\"NASA\">NASA<\/a> to send clear pictures to Earth back from space.<sup id=\"cite_ref-LA_Times_Obit_10-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Willard_S._Boyle#cite_note-LA_Times_Obit-10\"><span>[<\/span>10<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> It is also the technology that powers many digital cameras today. Smith said of their invention: \"After making the first couple of imaging devices, we knew for certain that chemistry photography was dead.\" <sup id=\"cite_ref-Cassingham_2011_11-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Willard_S._Boyle#cite_note-Cassingham_2011-11\"><span>[<\/span>11<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>Boyle was Executive Director of Research for Bell Labs from 1975 until his retirement in 1979.<sup id=\"cite_ref-LA_Times_Obit_10-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Willard_S._Boyle#cite_note-LA_Times_Obit-10\"><span>[<\/span>10<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> In retirement, he split his time between Halifax and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Wallace,_Nova_Scotia\" title=\"Wallace, Nova Scotia\">Wallace, Nova Scotia<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Amherst_Obit_12-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Willard_S._Boyle#cite_note-Amherst_Obit-12\"><span>[<\/span>12<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> In Wallace, he helped launch an art gallery with his wife Betty, a landscape artist.<sup id=\"cite_ref-big_idea_6-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Willard_S._Boyle#cite_note-big_idea-6\"><span>[<\/span>6<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> He was married to Betty since 1947, and had four children, 10 grandchildren and one great-grandchild.<sup id=\"cite_ref-CBC_5-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Willard_S._Boyle#cite_note-CBC-5\"><span>[<\/span>5<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> He was appointed a Companion of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Order_of_Canada\" title=\"Order of Canada\">Order of Canada<\/a> \u2014 the award's highest level \u2014 on June 30, 2010.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Order_of_Canada_13-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Willard_S._Boyle#cite_note-Order_of_Canada-13\"><span>[<\/span>13<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> In his later years, Boyle suffered from kidney disease, and due to complications from this disease, died in a hospital in Wallace on May 7, 2011.<sup id=\"cite_ref-LA_Times_Obit_10-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Willard_S._Boyle#cite_note-LA_Times_Obit-10\"><span>[<\/span>10<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p>","name":"Willard S. Boyle","place_of_birth":"Amherst ,  Nova Scotia ,  Canada","place_of_death":"Wallace ,  Nova Scotia ,  Canada","text":"Willard S. Boyle ,  born in Canada , Physics, 2009","year":2009.0}